<subSubSection id="D957771626CE7F82B64D1BF38AB95568" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="species composition">
<paragraph id="FF24AB945A6036BE1AB9B7077B6A83B1" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Species composition.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2844339E02EF5EC948DA99291520C06B" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
Most Palearctic species fall into a rather homogenous group of species referred to here as the 
<taxonomicName id="EF2B89C2E149717702BF6DCCCA921FC0" lsidName="albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">albisecta</taxonomicName>
group (
<taxonomicName id="2A9FE67633C6ED6D1B2CDC572802B0C2" authority="Tkalcu, 1967" authorityName="Tkalcu" authorityYear="1967" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Metamegachile" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Metamegachile" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Metamegachile</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="17F7819FBD8AFE020D8BC1A02FB0E4B9" originalValue="Tkalců">Tkalcu</normalizedToken>
, 1967), even if the structure of T7 is rather different in 
<taxonomicName id="B26C300B8C19CB46D39C2F4F3FE56EA6" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile doriae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="doriae">Megachile doriae</taxonomicName>
; there are at least four valid species in this group: 
<taxonomicName id="CC481C364CD46C1769AE9B32EA9DB36F" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="11FEBF782DC0E71802DE71A694E42FC5" genus="M." lsidName="M. amabilis" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="amabilis">M. amabilis</taxonomicName>
Cockerell, 1933, 
<taxonomicName id="F4E22D0204AA7700822BAC066284B68A" genus="M." lsidName="M. doriae" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="doriae">M. doriae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="CA115D78D0C56B8D87E7A008474FE43A" genus="M." lsidName="M. morawitzi" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="morawitzi">M. morawitzi</taxonomicName>
Radoszkowski, 1876; a fifth is undescribed (A. Monfared and C. Praz, in prep). The status of 
<taxonomicName id="86A56F77077CC791DDCC61925C36DDB5" genus="M." lsidName="M. ghigii" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="ghigii">M. ghigii</taxonomicName>
Gribodo, 1924, described from Libya, and 
<taxonomicName id="1092474D9C216E8BE83FA84CE7C48B00" genus="M." lsidName="M. aurantiaca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">M. aurantiaca</taxonomicName>
Rebmann, 1972 from Iran (a junior homonym of 
<taxonomicName id="371D5904058C5CB78FAF63FFBCFA2919" genus="M." lsidName="M. aurantiaca" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="aurantiaca">M. aurantiaca</taxonomicName>
Friese, 1905) as well as of numerous Central Asian taxa related to 
<taxonomicName id="A600A7A5C48EA4AF551F6AAFD3904DC6" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
remains unclear. On the Arabian Peninsula, additional species with Afrotropical affinities occur: 
<bibRefCitation id="662F44C62E582D8784CFEB7E3C9DB869" author="Pasteels, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin et annales de la Societe royale belge d'entomologie" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="250 - 257" title="Notes sur de Megachilidae (Hymenoptera, Apoidea) d'Arabie et des regions desertiques limitrophes. 1. Quelques especes a affinite africaine." volume="115" year="1979">Pasteels (1979)</bibRefCitation>
placed 
<taxonomicName id="BCC4736A12E436D25E9DF3C7AE291698" genus="M." lsidName="M. arabica" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="arabica">M. arabica</taxonomicName>
in the aurivilli group (see 
<bibRefCitation id="5B4CED013DA94CA7BB93F37EE7C8D627" author="Pasteels, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Musee Royal de l'Afrique Centrale, Annales Serie 8, Sciences Zoologiques 137, Tervuren, Belgium" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" title="Revision des Megachilidae (HymenopteraApoidea) de l'Afrique Noire, 1. Les genres Creightoniella [sic], Chalicodoma et Megachile (s. str.)." year="1965">Pasteels 1965</bibRefCitation>
) and 
<taxonomicName id="020159D9C6EFCE0FE0B7C4911AD9F596" genus="M." lsidName="M. felix" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="felix">M. felix</taxonomicName>
(Pasteels, 1979), known only in the female sex, in the angulata group. Mentions of 
<taxonomicName id="17F5FFA14F95A58C58F0BCD542FCEF4F" genus="M." lsidName="M. sudanica" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="sudanica">M. sudanica</taxonomicName>
Magretti, 1898 from Jordan (
<bibRefCitation id="7560D931DB502705BF1C58CA8C7F736E" author="Zanden, G van der" journalOrPublisher="Entomologische Abhandlungen, Staatliches Museum fuer Tierkunde Dresden" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="71 - 86" title="Neue oder wenig bekannte Arten und Unterarten der palaearktischen Megachiliden (Insecta, Hymenoptera, Apoidea: Megachilidae)." volume="53" year="1989">Zanden 1989</bibRefCitation>
) possibly refer to 
<taxonomicName id="D2828C6565819E274998ABB2641B9E9A" genus="M." lsidName="M. arabica" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="arabica">M. arabica</taxonomicName>
, and both species may be conspecific (
<bibRefCitation id="70B8BEFD621A25D8540E89B27626767F" author="Pasteels, JJ" journalOrPublisher="Musee Royal de l'Afrique Centrale, Annales Serie 8, Sciences Zoologiques 137, Tervuren, Belgium" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" title="Revision des Megachilidae (HymenopteraApoidea) de l'Afrique Noire, 1. Les genres Creightoniella [sic], Chalicodoma et Megachile (s. str.)." year="1965">Pasteels 1965</bibRefCitation>
: 26). In addition, I have seen a single specimen putatively from Yemen (BMNH) of an African species with a modified clypeus, possibly either 
<taxonomicName id="551B65F599697BBC1FD6023ADFE2219A" genus="M." lsidName="M. bicornuta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="bicornuta">M. bicornuta</taxonomicName>
Friese, 1903 or 
<taxonomicName id="56BDB384FA27FE1070CB4BDD07BE7B8B" genus="M." lsidName="M. cornigera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="cornigera">M. cornigera</taxonomicName>
Friese, 1904, both in the African 
<taxonomicName id="74A0B60DBF0E7290BC6AC76CE0825DEE" lsidName="cornigera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="cornigera">cornigera</taxonomicName>
group.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7BA2D233537728E1EFB5AE0EFA2948A4" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="29BBB3CCD5C3A1326098A9B60C28AD55" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">Biology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E6CA935B003246179E8883A41EB34DE5" pageId="9" pageNumber="10">
The nesting biology of 
<taxonomicName id="F0C9A95466EA1A3E016E35AB7BEF539F" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Megachile" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Megachile albisecta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albisecta">Megachile albisecta</taxonomicName>
has been described in detail (
<bibRefCitation id="30103F97D7083323714C0430ADE4067C" author="Ferton, C" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la societe entomologique de France" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="83 - 149" title="Notes detachees sur l'instinct des Hymenopteres melliferes et ravisseurs avec la description de quelques especes." volume="70" year="1901">Ferton 1901</bibRefCitation>
). This species nests in burrows in the ground; whether the females dig their own burrows or rent existing cavities as suggested by Ferton is not clear, although a brief description of a nest by 
<bibRefCitation id="330D1AA5B6BCA43987EA9080707ED0BB" author="Grandi, G" journalOrPublisher="Bollettino dell'Istituto di Entomologia dell'Universita di Bologna" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" title="Studi di un entomologo sugli imenotteri superiori" volume="25" year="1961">Grandi (1961)</bibRefCitation>
mentions a nest &quot;excavated in very hard soil&quot; [the Oriental species 
<taxonomicName id="6E8F557116A522A7804919D32E70932C" genus="M." lsidName="M. frontalis" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="frontalis">M. frontalis</taxonomicName>
(Fabricius, 1804) consistently digs its own burrows in hard, heavy soils (
<bibRefCitation id="F0F943434A8964223FDF3B767D69047D" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Papua and New Guinea Agricultural Journal" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="22 - 35" title="Observations on the biology of a leafcutter bee &quot; Megachilefrontalis, &quot; in New Guinea." volume="13" year="1960">Michener and Szent-Ivany 1960</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="F4B4366F27E1B1294622E856143168EB" author="Willmer, PG" journalOrPublisher="Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="113 - 124" title="Incidence of entomophilous pollination of lowland coffee (Coffeacanephora); the role of leaf cutter bees in Papua New Guinea." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1570-7458.1989.tb02380.x" volume="50" year="1989">Willmer and Stone 1989</bibRefCitation>
]. Reports of nests in dead wood (
<bibRefCitation id="2767489CBED867D3544DD6A56B1472AD" author="Benoist, R" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="41 - 88" title="Remarques sur quelques especes de megachiles principalement de la faune francaise." volume="109" year="1940">Benoist 1940</bibRefCitation>
) and in stems (
<bibRefCitation id="C4C3E89CD8737F5D8FFD6D880C57536F" author="Banaszak, J" journalOrPublisher="Bydgoszcz University, Bydgoszcz" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" title="Megachilid bees of Europe (Hymenoptera, Apoidea, Megachilidae)." year="2001">Banaszak and Romasenko 2001</bibRefCitation>
) are likely identification errors. Unlike the circular leaf discs cut by 
<taxonomicName id="AF0ECE154EA9D8553F6FE19D6D2C931D" genus="M." lsidName="M. frontalis" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="frontalis">M. frontalis</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation id="DB5545432800614A1EB13B86F3750787" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Papua and New Guinea Agricultural Journal" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="22 - 35" title="Observations on the biology of a leafcutter bee &quot; Megachilefrontalis, &quot; in New Guinea." volume="13" year="1960">Michener and Szent-Ivany 1960</bibRefCitation>
: Plate 1), the leaf fragments used by 
<taxonomicName id="6CC9DB9A32388C2FDF7F64A4C94AF75C" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
are irregular; in 
<taxonomicName id="33C85911F3AE92B8081A50B807CE8434" genus="M." lsidName="M. frontalis" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="frontalis">M. frontalis</taxonomicName>
, the leaf fragments used for the outer layer of the cells are also irregular (
<bibRefCitation id="295620A6DD92F928C308D990A67E4125" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Papua and New Guinea Agricultural Journal" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="22 - 35" title="Observations on the biology of a leafcutter bee &quot; Megachilefrontalis, &quot; in New Guinea." volume="13" year="1960">Michener and Szent-Ivany 1960</bibRefCitation>
: 31 and Plate 3; 
<bibRefCitation id="8E878D0FB9BA221A4EEB0666BAC9193D" author="Willmer, PG" journalOrPublisher="Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="113 - 124" title="Incidence of entomophilous pollination of lowland coffee (Coffeacanephora); the role of leaf cutter bees in Papua New Guinea." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1570-7458.1989.tb02380.x" volume="50" year="1989">Willmer and Stone 1989</bibRefCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName id="29B82643D76F12C1C03022BD0D71FDD7" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
the fragments are stuck together by masticated leaf material, and the entire cell rests on a solid plug of masticated leaf pulp mixed with pebbles. The nest plug consists of circular leaf fragments and pebbles cemented together by masticated leaf pulp. Nests of 
<taxonomicName id="092D658F10587B9230CB98268805A39C" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
do not appear to include resin according to the description by 
<bibRefCitation id="3A54E6BE47B183C94855EEC8E296EDF3" author="Ferton, C" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la societe entomologique de France" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="83 - 149" title="Notes detachees sur l'instinct des Hymenopteres melliferes et ravisseurs avec la description de quelques especes." volume="70" year="1901">Ferton (1901)</bibRefCitation>
, although 
<normalizedToken id="20F9D6E5C41F7319F47B9C34A9CFCD6C" originalValue="Ferton’s">Ferton's</normalizedToken>
subsequent articles (
<bibRefCitation id="68C4766D53EF612F789B60252BA14DC3" author="Ferton, C" journalOrPublisher="Annales de la Societe Entomologique de France" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" pagination="535 - 586" title="Notes detachees sur l'instinct des hymenopteres melliferes et ravisseurs (4 eme serie) avec la description de quelques especes." volume="77" year="1908">Ferton 1908</bibRefCitation>
: 547) suggest that resin was included in the nest. Possibly the leaf pulp is hardened with secretions but not resin. Resin was not found in the nests of 
<taxonomicName id="E547B8CDE7E95012365AD96FB08359EF" genus="M." lsidName="M. frontalis" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="frontalis">M. frontalis</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="A40797519558232F10B5535E18788FDB" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Papua and New Guinea Agricultural Journal" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="22 - 35" title="Observations on the biology of a leafcutter bee &quot; Megachilefrontalis, &quot; in New Guinea." volume="13" year="1960">Michener and Szent-Ivany 1960</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="984DF8EE51ADF4D7AD6FB7D50D74E169" author="Willmer, PG" journalOrPublisher="Entomologia Experimentalis et Applicata" pageId="25" pageNumber="26" pagination="113 - 124" title="Incidence of entomophilous pollination of lowland coffee (Coffeacanephora); the role of leaf cutter bees in Papua New Guinea." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1570-7458.1989.tb02380.x" volume="50" year="1989">Willmer and Stone 1989</bibRefCitation>
) but was reported from the nest of the African 
<taxonomicName id="E230567F4CEB8C9079232098D9BED3AD" genus="M." lsidName="M. cornigera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="cornigera">M. cornigera</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="9CFD926BCDA67C4652E5668A99E7C607" author="Michener, CD" journalOrPublisher="Journal of the Entomological Society of Southern Africa" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="337 - 359" title="Nest of some African Megachilid bees, with description of a new Hoplitis (Hymenoptera, Apoidea)." volume="31" year="1968">Michener 1968</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="7FBE5DE440FCF44A89148DB477C2AAD5" genus="M." lsidName="M. arabica" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="arabica">M. arabica</taxonomicName>
has been observed cutting leaf discs (H. Priesner, cited in 
<bibRefCitation id="2EDB53FC6D51B3AF121E9CAFC7B62735" author="Alfken, JD" journalOrPublisher="Bulletin de la Societe Royale Entomologique d'Egypte" pageId="20" pageNumber="21" pagination="146 - 163" title="Beitrag zur Kenntnis der Megachile-Arten von Aegypten." volume="18" year="1934">Alfken 1934</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName id="FFF47569FF85ADAF5622D4BD471D0972" genus="M." lsidName="M. albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">M. albisecta</taxonomicName>
(and possibly all species of the 
<taxonomicName id="D667A3F476EBB7602B43AA05F9C97CE5" lsidName="albisecta" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="species" species="albisecta">albisecta</taxonomicName>
group) is oligolectic on 
<taxonomicName id="77AAEB40FC15D2BDC5686A3FEDF8D4CF" family="Asteraceae" lsidName="" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" rank="family">Asteraceae</taxonomicName>
, with a preference for 
<taxonomicName id="0362447F63B8BAE5D58883310A5527D1" authority="" authorityName="" class="Insecta" family="Megachilidae" genus="Carduoideae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Carduoideae" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="10" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subfamily" subfamily="Carduoideae">Carduoideae</taxonomicName>
(C. Praz, unpublished data).
</paragraph>
